May 14 2006	Best Option in Chicago	First, a little background. I grew up in Chicago, and lived in Lakeview for over ten years before moving to Amsterdam. My wife is British, and her family used to run a bed &amp; breakfast in Devon, UK. I say this because at this point in time I think we are in a good position to recoomend the Majestic. This hotel does a good job of providing a relaxing atmosphere. It has a European/English B&amp;B feel in that the rooms vary in size, has a nice sitting area, no parking facility, and is on a quaint residential street. My wife felt more comfortable here than any other place we have stayed when in the states. Yes, many of the rooms have next to no view, but same can be said about many of the rooms in downtown Chicago as well most of the hotels in London. For a leisure traveller to Chicago (without kids), it has the most important quality a hotel needs to have: a very comfortable place to start and end each day. For travelers with kids, there is this concept called a CITY PARK literally two blocks away; complete with playgound, tennis courts, softball fields, a beach for dogs, a golf course, and even a totem pole.The hotel is a little over four miles north of the loop, Navy Pier, Millenium Park, and Grant Park. Being a half block off the lake, it is a perfect distance for an early morning run before work or play. There are options of a free quick continental breakfast in the hotel or a number of good breakfast places nearby, such as Ann Sathers, IHOP, or Nookies. There is a Starbucks, Einstien's bagels, and Caribou Coffee within walking distance. All of which are not far off the path to the El, and have high cab traffic going by.As far as the parking goes, if your willing to walk a couple blocks and willing to abide by the closing hours, there is the option of parking on the other side of Lake Shore Drive in the park. As far as the elevator, gimme a break. The place is only four stories high including the ground floor.A hotel should compliment a vacation, not BE the vacation. The Majestic as a perfect compliment.	
May 7 2006	Alway Spectacular	Love the Majestic. Great location for nightlife and sports (Wrigley is within walking distance). The red line is only a couple of blocks away. Rooms are well appointed and clean. If you are looking for a large hotel with restaraunts and things for the kids to do, this isn't it. If you are looking for a elegant boutique hotel refuge from the hustle and bustle of the city, this is your place.	
Apr 23 2006	Impeccably clean awesome beds outstanding staff at the Majestic!	Recently I had to rush to Chicago to see my adult son who was in the hospital. I went right from the airport to the hospital. Upon arriving at the Majestic Hotel I was exhausted. I was greeted by a charming woman who recognized how tired I was and wanted me to be comfortable. I had booked a suite ahead of time in the hopes that my son could stay with me a couple of days upon discharge from the hospital. I was shown a couple of different rooms and asked which one I wanted. The beds are incredibly comfortable and the rooms immaculate. The hotel is in a very quiet neighborhood near wonderful restaurants and bus lines for easy access to downtown Chicago.As it turned out, my stay at the Majestic Hotel was 10 nights! I was treated like family. As a matter of fact, my husband and parents joined me toward the end of the stay and they also couldn’t say enough wonderful things about the Majestic Hotel and its staff.If you want wonderful beds, clean and quiet rooms, free continental breakfast (with excellent coffee- I am pretty particular about my coffee), check out this hotel. My family and I will definitely stay there when we visit Chicago again.Having traveled with children for years I know the kind of activities and environment they enjoy. The Majestic does not have the water activities and play areas that children and their parents enjoy. However, if you want a quiet, comfortable stay with delightful staff, then stay at the Majestic. My thanks especially to Sarita for accommodating my schedule and room requests and particularly that upgrade for my mom and dad to that beautiful suite with the porch.Thank you also to Dana, Uzi and Roxanna- you guys are terrific. Thank you. We will be back!	
Mar 23 2006	Wish I had researched better	This hotel was easy to find and had a nice location. The rooms were nice, comfortable and clean. The atmosphere was elegant. That sums up all the good things about this hotel. For the price we paid to stay there for five nights, we were very disappointed, right from the beginning. When we arrived at the hotel with our children (no extra little perks for kids by the way) and our many bags, we were not offered any help with our luggage. We struggled into the hotel with kids in tow and had no idea where to park or how to get all our bags in while blocking the street. The lady at the desk directed my husband where to park (which was a parking garage you entered by going around the block)(leaving out the information on how to get back in the building without walking around the entire block) and after asking if I needed help with all of our luggage, (FINALLY), she, rather than grabbing any bags, picked up my two year old son. We spotted a rack to put all our bags on (rather than her letting us know there was one) and we then had to squeeze luggage and family into their very small elevator to get to our room. Never having been to Chicago, and arriving close to dinnertime, we were hungry and had no idea where to go for food. This hotel has no restaurants and no room service (the few times we called down to ask a question or needed something we were told to come down to the desk and they would help us). Therefore, the first night we asked the front desk where a family might go to eat a family friendly casual dinner within walking distance. They sent us to an Italian candleit restaurant (granted, within walking distance) where our children had no room to be comfortable and we could not even read the menu. We left there shortly after we arrived and instead walked to a carry out place we had spotted two doors down that had a very family friendly menu and atmosphere. (thank goodness) As far as breakfast, the Majestic does have a continental breakfast consisting of juice, coffee, bagels and croissants. However, not something you want to eat every morning for any length of time. They offer cookies and coffee in the evening. They are supposed to offer coffee and tea 24 hours a day but more than twice when I attempted to get coffee the canisters were empty. As far as friendliness, they always had a smile for my son when we came out of our room, but not even a hello to my daughter or the rest of the family. We enjoyed our daytimes in Chicago, but found in the evenings, we were stuck in the hotel with nothing to do. This hotel was a definite disappointment. If ever a next time in Chicago, we will definitely better research where to stay and find a place with a pool, a restaurant (and room service) and friendlier and more helpful staff for the money we shelled out at the Majestic.	
Mar 2 2006	From a regular...	I've stayed at the Majestic multiple times in the past. I can't get over how wonderful this place is - very elegant with it's European charm. The front desk staff is always on top of things - one of the front desk employees, Savita, is amazing. She goes above and beyond to meet guest expectations!The majestic is a great place to stay for the &quot;gay high holidays&quot; such as Pride, Market Days, etc - book early because vacancy goes fast. The hotel is situated on a quiet street in Lakeview - very close to the North Halsted nightlife and the action of Broadway Ave.I will continue to stay at this hotel in the future!	
Feb 19 2006	Boutique is the right word	Boutique is the right word for this hotel. My flight back east was cancelled due to February blizzard and I was very pleased to find the Majestic--great quality at $89. Rooms are small but mine was quiet, lovely toiletries and comfy robe, good mattress and bedding, very friendly and helpful staff, elevator is european (tiny), but, hey, it beats the stairs with luggage. Breakfast not special, but available in a nice setting. And everything very clean, the whole hotel is non-smoking. We stay at so-called boutique hotels in New York City now and then and have found that means small, dark, and not all that clean, so this was a nice surprise. And location is terrific, near the lake and everything else on the North side.	
Feb 7 2006	Good Clean and Affordable	Stayed here on a trip to visit a friend and found the accomodations to be very nice. It is an older building with some charm. The people who work there are friendly and it feels more like a B &amp; B than a hotel. The library or lobby area is very nice with a fire place and coffee available 24hrs. The elevator is small but functional. The room was nice, clean and very roomy. The bed was the best part. It was firm and nice---had the best sleep while I was there. The TV is small and the shower head was good. There is no restaurant but some neighborhood restaurants near by and a supermarket within walking distance. All in all a good decent place not fancy but comfy.	
Jan 17 2006	Majestic Majestic	Stayed at the Majestic this past weekend. I love this hotel. This is the second time I have stayed here and had an even better experience. It is a European style hotel with a lot of charm. It is convenient to the Wrigleyville and &quot;Boystown&quot; area. Located on a quiet street. The rooms are small, but comfortable. The rooms are very clean and nicely decorated. The bed was comfortable. The bathroom was also very clean and seemed updated. They also had very nice and high quality products in the bathroom (shampoo, conditioner, shower gel, and bath salts). The robes were a nice touch. The staff was professional and friendly. Check out time is 11:00 a.m. - they allowed us to stay until 1:00 p.m. because we had a later flight that evening. All in all, a great experience.	
Nov 22 2005	Great Hotel	We stayed at the Majestic over memorial weekend and the stay was fabulous. The rooms aren't smaller than normal than from your standard cookie cutter hotels but the hotel has charm. Very cozy place to stay with it fine sitting room that is used for their continental breakfast. Its so comfortable and it makes it easy for people to feel at home. short blocks to wrigley field, and even shorter walk to the L to get all over the city. We love the area with its great dining, little shops and full size grocery/ pharm for everything you may forgotten	
Nov 1 2005 	A Majestic Experience	I truly debated whether or not we should stay at this hotel given some of the negative reviews on this website. But I am happy to report that we experienced nothing but a wonderful time at the Majestic and plan on returning there when we next visit Chicago. The front desk personnel were very friendly and extremely thoughtful. We were able to get into a fully booked restaurant thanks to their help. The hotel is just a short walk from just about any shopping or dining option you can think of. Our room was lovely (queen suite) and with every amenity one could expect. My response to those who found the Majestic less than satisfactory---if don't want to walk up stairs, if you think your car should be parked right outside your room, if you think all hotel rooms should be as big as your house, and if old-fashioned heating systems keep you up at night, don't stay in an historic urban boutique hotel! Perhaps a nice Hampton Inn is more your style? But if you are looking for charming, intimate, and unique lodging on the North Side of Chicago, consider booking a room at the Majestic.	
Aug 26 2005 	Ups and downs	I have stayed at the Majestic for a couple of times during tha last ten years. Very nice neighborhood, and it by now feel like home away from home. But the rooms have very different quality (avoid rooms near the elevator!), the breakfast has deteriorated during the years (alsthough it was always plastic). The bathrooms are mostly ok, the toiletries supplied are excellent, the parlour where tea and breakfast are supplied is a nice cozy reading room (for those who need this in Chicago). Very friendly, helpful an knowledgable staff.	
